<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<section xml:id="sec-s02e05" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Episode 5: PEMDAS Integers</title>
<assemblage>
    <title>Episode Learning Goals</title>
    <p>
        <ul>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Perform multi-step calculations involving integers.
                </p>
            </li>
        </ul>
    </p>
</assemblage>
<p>
    The same rules of PEMDAS apply when working with integers
</p>
<example>
    <p>
        Calculate
        <md>
            -[3-4(6\div 2)^2]
        </md>
    </p>
    <p>
        Solution: First, we work on the calculation inside the innermost parentheses, <m>6\div 2</m>:
        <md>
            -[3-4(3)^2]
        </md>
        Then, we work on the calculation inside the brackets, <m>3-4(3)^2</m>. Applying PEMDAS here, we calculate the exponent <m>(3)^2</m> next:
        <md>
            -[3-4(9)]
        </md>
        We calculate the multiplication next:
        <md>
         -3[3-36]   
        </md>
        Then the subtraction:
        <md>
            -[-33]
        </md>
        Finally, we remember that the extra - is telling us to find the opposite of -33. So our answer is
        <md>
            -[-33] = 33
        </md>
    </p>
</example>
<assemblage>
    <title>Be Careful</title>
    <p>
       There is a difference between
       <md>
        -3^2 \quad \text{and} \quad (-3)^2
       </md>
        By default, an exponent only applies to the single symbol directly underneath it. So in <m>-3^2</m> only the 3 is getting copied, not the <m>-</m>:
        <md>
            -3^2 = -3\times 3 = -9
        </md>
        If you want to copy the entire quantity -3, then you need to wrap -3 in parentheses before applying the exponent, like in <m>(-3)^2</m>:
        <md>
            (-3)^2 = -3 \times -3 = 9
        </md>
    </p>
</assemblage>

<xi:include href="ws-s02e05.ptx" />
</section>